A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fconsent-farms-spam-calls-robocalls-do-not-call-list-2023-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ephone%20call%20from%20an%20unknown%20number%3C%2Fa%3E%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you're%20like%20most%20Americans%2C%20it's%20probably%20been%20months%20since%20you%20took%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhy-so-many-spam-robocalls-how-to-stop-them-2021-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Echance%20with%20a%20random%20caller%3C%2Fa%3E.%20The%20growing%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Frobocalls-deep-fakes-new-era-because-of-ai-experts-say-2024-1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eprevalence%20of%20phone%20spam%3C%2Fa%3E%20isn't%20just%20an%20all-too-frequent%20headache%20for%20people%20going%20about%20their%20days%20but%20also%20something%20warping%20the%20way%20we%20understand%20and%20treat%20the%20US%20economy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEconomics%20has%20a%20variety%20of%20tools%20that%20can%20help%20us%20figure%20out%20which%20parts%20of%20society%20are%20winning%20and%20which%20are%20losing.%20Some%20of%20these%20tools%20are%20what's%20known%20as%20%26quot%3Bhard%20data%2C%26quot%3B%20detailed%20datasets%20that%20actually%20measure%20things%20such%20as%20the%20output%20of%20businesses%20and%20household%20spending.%20Then%20there%20is%20%26quot%3Bsoft%20data%2C%26quot%3B%20surveys%20and%20polls%20that%20help%20us%20understand%20the%20lived%20experience%20of%20Americans%20%E2%80%94%20how%20they%20feel%20about%20the%20economy%2C%20how%20they%20expect%20their%20finances%20to%20change%2C%20and%20where%20they%20think%20the%20country%20is%20headed.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESince%20the%20onset%20of%20the%20pandemic%2C%20America's%20economy%20has%20been%20bizarre%20in%20many%20ways%2C%20but%20there%20has%20been%20one%20especially%20hard-to-explain%20divergence%20that%20should%20worry%20everyone.%20The%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Frecession-outlook-economy-good-inflation-jobs-wages-2023-12%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehard%20data%20is%20telling%20a%20story%20of%20a%20strong%20recovery%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%20Frontline%20workers%20and%20lower-income%20households%20have%20been%20riding%20a%20turbocharged%20job%20market%20that%20has%20boosted%20GDP%20growth.%20But%20the%20soft%2C%20survey-based%20data%20is%20telling%20a%20different%20story%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fstudent-loans-housing-costs-chatgpt-why-americans-feel-bad-economy-2023-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EHouseholds%20report%20massive%20economic%20pessimism%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20is%20more%20consistent%20with%20periods%20of%20extremely%20high%20unemployment%2C%20low%20economic%20growth%2C%20and%20general%20economic%20disaster.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20have%20been%20plenty%20of%20explanations%20for%20the%20divergence%2C%20but%20one%20reason%20is%20that%20the%20quality%20of%20the%20soft%20data%20we're%20getting%20is%20deteriorating.%20Fewer%20people%20are%20responding%20to%20surveys%20about%20the%20economy%2C%20and%20those%20who%20do%20are%20more%20likely%20to%20be%20downplaying%20the%20positive%20aspects%20of%20our%20recovery.%20By%20underweighting%20the%20experience%20of%20certain%20groups%20%E2%80%94%20especially%20lower-income%20or%20frontline%20workers%20%E2%80%94%20policymakers%20could%20learn%20the%20wrong%20lessons%20from%20the%20post-pandemic%20economy.%20Without%20people%20seeing%20it%20as%20the%20most%20successful%20recession%20bounce%20back%20in%20history%2C%20this%20distorted%20view%20could%20push%20leaders%20to%20return%20to%20their%20bad%20habits%20from%20the%201980s%20to%202010s%2C%20when%20the%20fear%20of%20inflation%20and%20muted%20recession%20responses%20helped%20drive%20income%20inequality%2C%20left%20people%20out%20of%20work%20for%20longer%2C%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.aeaweb.org%2Farticles%3Fid%3D10.1257%2Fapp.20190297%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eeven%20increased%20the%20mortality%3C%2Fa%3E%20rate%20among%20less-educated%20Americans.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EReturning%20to%20the%20bad%20old%20days%20of%20cautious%20post-recession%20policies%20wouldn't%20just%20leave%20people%20poorer%20and%20slow%20down%20our%20economic%20growth%2C%20it%20would%20also%20be%20the%20result%20of%20a%20serious%20failure%20to%20listen%20to%20the%20voices%20and%20experiences%20of%20working%20Americans.%20To%20avoid%20this%20fate%2C%20we%20have%20to%20make%20serious%20efforts%20to%20change%20how%20we%20measure%20and%20talk%20about%20the%20US%20economy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EThe%20Great%20Divergence%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20ask%20Americans%20how%20the%20economy%20is%20doing%2C%20the%20general%20sentiment%20can%20be%20summed%20up%20in%20one%20word%3A%20bad.%20The%20University%20of%20Michigan's%20consumer%20confidence%20index%20hit%20a%20record%20low%20in%20June%202022%2C%20and%20while%20there%20has%20been%20a%20slight%20rebound%20recently%2C%20it%20remains%20below%20its%20long-term%20average.%20Similarly%2C%20the%20Conference%20Board's%20consumer%20confidence%20data%20isn't%20quite%20at%20its%20post-Great%20Recession%20lows%2C%20but%20it's%20far%20below%20its%202017-19%20average.%20Polls%20that%20ask%20Americans%20about%20the%20direction%20of%20the%20economy%20are%20also%20bleak%20with%20the%20share%20saying%20the%20country%20is%20headed%20in%20the%20right%20direction%20hitting%20a%20record%20low%20of%2017.4%25%20in%20July%202022%2C%20according%20to%20the%20RealClearPolitics%20polling%20average.%20While%20that%20has%20since%20rebounded%20to%20about%2023%25%2C%20it%20remains%20weak%20historically.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2F3ywVV%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Consumer%20sentiment%3A%20General%20weakness%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EBy%20contrast%2C%20most%20of%20the%20hard%20data%20is%20exceptionally%20strong.%20Real%20GDP%20growth%20has%20risen%203%25%20a%20year%20from%202020%20to%202024%2C%20above%20the%202.4%25%20annual%20average%20from%202010%20to%202019%3B%20real%20consumer%20spending%20has%20risen%203.8%25%20a%20year%20versus%202.4%25%20a%20year%20pre-COVID%3B%20and%20the%20job%20market%20is%20strong%2C%20with%20nearly%20record%20low%20unemployment.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20reason%20for%20this%20break%20between%20soft%20and%20hard%20data%20may%20lie%20in%20%3Cem%3Ewhom%20%3C%2Fem%3Ethe%20economy%20is%20helping%20to%20lift%20up.%20The%20Bureau%20of%20Labor%20Statistics'%20metric%20for%20average%20hourly%20earnings%2C%20which%20can%20be%20adjusted%20for%20changes%20in%20inflation%2C%20breaks%20out%20the%20wages%20of%20production%20and%20nonsupervisory%20workers%20%E2%80%94%20in%20other%20words%2C%20employees%20who%20are%20not%20managing%20other%20workers.%20The%20results%20are%20remarkable%3A%20Nonmanagerial%20workers%20saw%20their%20wages%20surge%20during%20the%20pandemic%2C%20jumping%20by%206%25%20between%20February%202020%20and%20its%20peak%20in%20April%202020.%20Inflation%20ate%20away%20at%20some%20of%20those%20gains%2C%20but%20the%20average%20nonmanager%20now%20earns%203.4%25%20more%20an%20hour%20than%20they%20did%20at%20the%20end%20of%202019%2C%20even%20when%20accounting%20for%20inflation.%20Without%20adjusting%20for%20inflation%2C%20they%20earn%2023.5%25%20more%20an%20hour.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FRl7rM%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Managerial%20vs%20non-managerial%20workers%3A%20Line%20workers%20getting%20raises%5Cn%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22500%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EIt's%20a%20very%20different%20story%20for%20managers.%20While%20they%20also%20saw%20their%20real%20wages%20surge%20during%20the%20pandemic's%20acute%20phase%2C%20inflation-adjusted%20average%20hourly%20earnings%20sank%20for%2025%20straight%20months%20%E2%80%94%20from%20January%202021%20to%20January%202023%20%E2%80%94%20and%20are%20now%20down%20by%20more%20than%207%25%20compared%20with%20the%20end%20of%202019.%20To%20be%20clear%2C%20managers%20still%20earn%2083%25%20more%20an%20hour%20on%20average%20than%20line%20workers%2C%20but%20the%20%3Cem%3Erelative%3C%2Fem%3E%20change%20in%20earnings%20after%20accounting%20for%20inflation%20is%20dramatic.%20While%20frontline%20employees%20saw%20pay%20rise%20as%20much%20as%20inflation%20and%20more%2C%20managerial%20workers%20got%20hammered.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOther%20data%20sources%20back%20up%20the%20pattern.%20The%20Census'%20most%20recent%20estimates%20of%20real%20median%20earnings%20showed%20incomes%20declining%20for%20almost%20every%20income%20bracket%20in%202022%20%E2%80%94%20except%20for%20workers%20in%20the%20bottom%2010%25%20of%20the%20income%20distribution.%20That%20group%20saw%20real%20incomes%20rise%20at%20a%20historic%20rate%2C%20while%20the%20wealthiest%20households%20got%20hit%20the%20hardest.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FBYrDB%2F2%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22The%20lowest-earning%20households%20were%20most%20protected%20from%202022's%20inflation%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Ch2%3EWho%20actually%20replies%20to%20surveys%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20why%20would%20that%20skew%20surveys%20asking%20how%20Americans%20feel%20about%20the%20economy%3F%20Surely%2C%20the%20gains%20for%20those%20at%20the%20bottom%20would%20offset%20the%20pessimism%20of%20everyone%20whose%20income%20sank.%20One%20explanation%20for%20the%20imbalance%20may%20come%20from%20whom%20the%20surveys%20are%20reaching.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EGovernment%20agencies%20and%20private%20pollsters%20alike%20are%20having%20an%20increasingly%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pewresearch.org%2Fshort-reads%2F2019%2F02%2F27%2Fresponse-rates-in-telephone-surveys-have-resumed-their-decline%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edifficult%20time%3C%2Fa%3E%20persuading%20Americans%20to%20respond%20to%20their%20questions.%20Response%20rates%20for%20the%20Bureau%20of%20Labor%20Statistics'%20monthly%20surveys%20have%20steadily%20collapsed%20over%20recent%20years%2C%20from%20about%2070%25%20a%20decade%20ago%20to%20roughly%2050%25%20in%202023.%20There%20are%20a%20variety%20of%20reasons%20for%20the%20rise%20in%20American%20blowing%20off%20surveys%3A%20wariness%20over%20telemarketers%2C%20a%20lack%20of%20interest%20in%20having%20their%20opinions%20heard%2C%20or%20a%20more%20general%20decline%20in%20the%20social%20trust%20that%20surveys%20rely%20on.%20No%20matter%20the%20reason%2C%20the%20rise%20in%20nonresponses%20makes%20it%20harder%20for%20economists%20to%20understand%20what%20people%20think.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FwaSz9%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Survey%20response%20rates%20have%20fallen%20broadly%2C%20both%20before%20and%20during%20COVID%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20the%20people%20who%20don't%20respond%20have%20something%20in%20common%2C%20that%20can%20skew%20the%20results%20of%20what%20would%2C%20on%20the%20face%20of%20it%2C%20seem%20like%20a%20useful%20survey.%20For%20instance%2C%20if%20you%20were%20trying%20to%20pick%20America's%20favorite%20NFL%20team%2C%20but%20only%20polite%20Midwesterners%20picked%20up%20the%20phone%20when%20you%20called%2C%20you%20might%20get%20the%20impression%20that%20Americans%20back%20only%20the%20Minnesota%20Vikings%2C%20Green%20Bay%20Packers%2C%20or%20Chicago%20Bears.%20In%20reality%2C%20a%20nonresponse%20bias%20has%20skewed%20the%20data.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20BLS%20and%20Bureau%20of%20Economic%20Analysis%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fapps.bea.gov%2Ffesac%2Fmeetings%2F2022-12-09%2FPickering-FESACNonresponse-in-Census-Surveys-12092022.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehave%20been%20careful%20to%20say%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20weak%20response%20rates%20aren't%20making%20their%20data%20unusable%2C%20but%20it%20requires%20a%20substantial%20amount%20of%20adjustment%20and%20government-exclusive%20data%20to%20make%20the%20results%20helpful.%20And%20if%20that%20kind%20of%20number%20crunching%20is%20a%20challenge%20for%20large%2C%20well-funded%20statistical%20agencies%2C%20then%20the%20task%20is%20even%20greater%20for%20private%20pollsters%20that%20survey%20only%20a%20few%20hundred%20households.%20For%20instance%2C%20Pew%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pewresearch.org%2Fshort-reads%2F2019%2F02%2F27%2Fresponse-rates-in-telephone-surveys-have-resumed-their-decline%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ereported%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%202019%20that%20the%20response%20rate%20for%20its%20telephone%20surveys%20had%20fallen%20from%20over%20one%20in%20three%20during%20the%20late%201990s%20to%20less%20than%2010%25%20by%20the%20late%202010s.%20Other%20pollsters%20have%20reported%20similar%20drops.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20with%20adjustments%2C%20surveys%20run%20the%20risk%20of%20missing%20out%20on%20certain%20chunks%20of%20the%20population.%20To%20try%20to%20figure%20out%20who%20the%20people%20are%20that%20it's%20most%20likely%20to%20miss%2C%20the%20Census%20Bureau%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.census.gov%2Fnewsroom%2Fblogs%2Fresearch-matters%2F2021%2F09%2Fpandemic-affect-survey-response.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eused%3C%2Fa%3E%202021%20administrative%20(nonsurvey)%20data%20to%20estimate%20the%20characteristics%20of%20households%20that%20did%20%3Cem%3Enot%20%3C%2Fem%3Erespond%20to%20its%20massive%20Current%20Population%20Survey's%20Annual%20Social%20and%20Economic%20Supplements.%20The%20ASEC%20data%20uses%20a%20very%20large%20sample%20to%20provide%20the%20best%20possible%20insight%20into%20households'%20economic%20well-being%2C%20with%20more%20than%2075%2C000%20households%20participating.%20Nonresponders%20skewed%20lower%20income%2C%20with%20the%20average%20responder%20earning%20about%20%245%2C000%20more%20than%20nonresponders%20in%202020%20and%202021.%20We%20can't%20know%20for%20certain%20what%20other%20kinds%20of%20nonresponse%20bias%20might%20be%20lurking%20out%20there%2C%20but%20we%20know%20concretely%20that%20even%20very%20large%2C%20comprehensive%20samples%20undercount%20lower-income%20people.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Census%20Bureau%20and%20other%20government%20agencies%20can%20adapt%20to%20that%20sort%20of%20bias%20because%20of%20the%20scale%20at%20which%20they're%20operating%20%E2%80%94%20the%20census%20had%20an%20annual%20budget%20of%20almost%20%241.4%20billion%20in%20fiscal%202022.%20But%20smaller%20operations%20paying%20for%20telephone%20surveys%20don't%20have%20the%20tools%20or%20resources%20to%20make%20similar%20adjustments%20to%20their%20samples.%20That%20suggests%20that%20even%20though%20private%20consumer%20confidence%20data%20attempts%20to%20account%20for%20income%20and%20other%20factors%2C%20it%20may%20be%20missing%20out%20on%20many%20of%20the%20people%20who%20are%20seeing%20the%20biggest%20benefits%20of%20the%20economy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EFlying%20blind%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20the%20football-fan%20example%20is%20an%20attempt%20at%20humor%2C%20the%20systemic%20underweighting%20of%20certain%20economic%20views%20has%20real-world%20consequences%20for%20how%20we%20talk%20about%20and%20treat%20the%20economy.%20For%20one%20thing%2C%20the%20more%20negative%2C%20managerial-class%20view%20of%20the%20economy%20has%20dominated%20most%20of%20the%20popular%20discussion%20over%20the%20past%20few%20years.%20Using%20a%20tracker%20that%20scans%20a%20slew%20of%20news%20sources%20for%20particular%20keywords%20and%20topics%2C%20we%20can%20see%20that%20inflation-related%20stories%20rose%20fourfold%20from%20the%20pre-COVID%20norm%20to%20the%20peak%20of%20inflation%20focus%20in%20early%202022.%20Similarly%2C%20the%20focus%20on%20the%20prospect%20of%20a%20recession%20soared%2C%20even%20outdoing%20the%20period%20in%202020%20when%20the%20economy%20was%20actually%20in%20a%20recession.%20By%20contrast%2C%20mentions%20of%20strong%20wages%20only%20modestly%20increased%20over%20the%20pre-COVID%20baseline.%20In%20other%20words%2C%20the%20huge%20gains%20made%20by%20low-income%20workers%20didn't%20make%20much%20of%20a%20blip%20in%20how%20the%20economy%20was%20discussed%2C%20while%20higher-income%20managerial%20workers'%20plight%20with%20inflation%20took%20center%20stage.%20While%20the%20financial%20media's%20bias%20toward%20negativity%20is%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nber.org%2Fpapers%2Fw32026%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epart%20of%20a%20longer-term%20problem%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20gap%20between%20good%20news%20and%20bad%20is%20staggering%20and%20asymmetric%3B%20it%20privileges%20the%20challenges%20of%20managers%20over%20the%20wins%20racked%20up%20by%20workers.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FvNhao%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22A%20four-fold%20inflation%20focus%2C%20but%20where%20are%20wages%3F%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20would%20be%20one%20thing%20if%20working%20people%20already%20had%20an%20equal%20seat%20at%20the%20policymaking%20table%2C%20but%20they%20do%20not.%20Federal%20Reserve%20officials%20read%20opinion%20columns%2C%20and%20congressional%20staffers%20browse%20social%20media.%20Skewing%20that%20information%20diet%20heavily%20toward%20the%20plight%20of%20higher%20earners%20can%20only%20further%20privilege%20their%20preferred%20outcomes%3A%20Fighting%20inflation%20comes%20first%2C%20and%20getting%20people%20back%20into%20jobs%20comes%20second.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20this%20wealth-skewed%20view%20wins%20out%20during%20the%20next%20recession%2C%20we%20can%20get%20a%20pretty%20clear%20picture%20of%20how%20things%20will%20play%20out%20%E2%80%94%20reducing%20inflation%2C%20%3Cem%3Eby%20definition%2C%3C%2Fem%3E%20seeks%20to%20reduce%20people's%20buying%20power%20and%20raise%20unemployment.%20That%20means%20less%20government%20stimulus%20in%20the%20event%20of%20a%20downturn%2C%20higher%20interest%20rates%2C%20and%20a%20willingness%20to%20let%20a%20recovery%20drag%20on.%20Reverting%20to%20our%20old%20way%20of%20dealing%20with%20recessions%20would%20also%20exacerbate%20inequality%3A%20Higher-income%20households%20are%20more%20likely%20to%20avoid%20losing%20their%20jobs%20and%20their%20wealth%20continues%20to%20grow%20as%20the%20stock%20market%20recovers%2C%20while%20on%20the%20other%20end%2C%20lower-income%20households%20face%20higher%20unemployment%20because%20of%20lower%20aggregate%20demand%20and%20weaker%20real%20wage%20growth%20due%20to%20weaker%20labor-bargaining%20power.%20All%20these%20factors%20serve%20to%20hurt%20the%20material%20conditions%20of%20working%20people%2C%20but%20they%20also%20concentrate%20political%20power%20in%20the%20hands%20of%20others.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20have%20been%20definitive%20winners%20and%20losers%20in%20the%20post-COVID%20economy.%20But%20how%20we%20measure%20the%20economy%20and%20listen%20to%20the%20voices%20of%20Americans%20has%20allowed%20the%20louder%2C%20wealthier%20voices%20to%20shape%20how%20leaders%20view%20the%20economic%20response.%20If%20we%20want%20policy%20that%20benefits%20working%20people%2C%20underweighting%20their%20experience%20in%20both%20%26quot%3Bsoft%26quot%3B%20and%20%26quot%3Bhard%26quot%3B%20data%20is%20a%20huge%20mistake.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fauthor%2Fgeorge-pearkes%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cu%3EGeorge%20Pearkes%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E%C2%A0is%20the%20Global%20Macro%20Strategist%20for%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%20nofollow%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bespokepremium.com%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cu%3EBespoke%20Investment%20Group%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpolls-get-american-economy-wrong-make-next-recession-worse-jobs-2024-3%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1710236521000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65ef65df90413ab8e1db81e8%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpolls-get-american-economy-wrong-make-next-recession-worse-jobs-2024-3%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%20way%20we%20measure%20and%20survey%20Americans%20has%20allowed%20the%20louder%2C%20angrier%2C%20wealthier%20voices%20to%20distort%20our%20view%20of%20the%20economy.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22george%40bespokeinvest.com%20(George%20Pearkes)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A2%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpolls-get-american-economy-wrong-make-next-recession-worse-jobs-2024-3%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Musheer%20breaks%20Sachin's%2029-year%20old%20record%20in%20Ranji%20final%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1710236346000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fstatic.toiimg.com%2Fphoto%2Fmsid-108431745%2Cimgsize-31926.cms%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com%2Fsports%2Fcricket%2Fnews%2Fmusheer-khan-breaks-sachin-tendulkars-29-year-old-recor